    {
        "content": "<div class=\"spoiler-block\"><div class=\"spoiler-header\">\n<p>Attempt <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/2\">#2</a></p>\n</div><div class=\"spoiler-content\" aria-hidden=\"true\">\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">universe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grothendieck_universe</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">class</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Universe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">setEquiv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">))</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">natEquiv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">sigma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">sigmaEquiv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">Σ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">sigma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"o\">))</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Might be a bit hard</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exists_universe_iff_exists_inaccessible</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nonempty</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Universe</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Cardinal</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">},</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">IsInaccessible</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">instance</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Universe</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PLift</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">sigma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">Σ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">setEquiv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">plift</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">trans</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">congr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">plift</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">symm</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">natEquiv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">plift</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">symm</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">sigmaEquiv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">trans</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">sigmaCongr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">plift</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">plift</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">plift</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">symm</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n</div></div>",
        "id": 526163521,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751068630
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The -&gt; direction should be that you would consider the map from \\a to Cardinal and then take the union.</p>\n<p>The &lt;- direction should be some sort of type-theoretic interpretation of V(\\a) where V is the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Neumann_universe\">von Neumann universe</a></p>",
        "id": 526164084,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751069235
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Am I understanding correctly that you are trying to write down the thing that lean cannot prove (because Type universes are themselves inaccessible but do not necessarily contain inaccessibles)?</p>",
        "id": 526165500,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071221
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110049\">Mario Carneiro</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Type.200.20contains.20a.20universe/near/526165500\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Am I understanding correctly that you are trying to write down the thing that lean cannot prove</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Correct.</p>",
        "id": 526165515,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071244
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A popular way to write this in type theory is to use inductive-recursive types</p>",
        "id": 526165536,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071278
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, that sounds fun, what does that mean?</p>",
        "id": 526165558,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071315
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure what the simplest inductive-recursive type that lean cannot prove (is equivalent to something that) exists is</p>",
        "id": 526165562,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071318
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>An inductive recursive type is when you define a function by recursion mutually with an inductive type</p>",
        "id": 526165580,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071348
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it can be used to define models of type theory where you have an inductive type that produces codes for types mutually with a decoding function which turns the codes into actual types</p>",
        "id": 526165611,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071404
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Am I understanding correctly that you basically want to express the fact that an inaccessible cardinal is the a fixed point of beth that is also closed under union? And you want to use recursion to produce a fixed point of beth as well as make it closed under union?</p>",
        "id": 526165651,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071457
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I mean it also sounds like that since you said Lean cannot prove that it exists, then there's no way to actually write down the <code>inductive</code> type?</p>",
        "id": 526165675,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071497
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>in fact you kind of did this with your axiomatization, you are defining <code>α</code> by induction and <code>obj : α → Type u</code> by recursion, mutually</p>",
        "id": 526165691,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071509
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see</p>",
        "id": 526165707,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071525
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can write down some syntax that would plausibly produce the object, except that lean doesn't support inductive recursive types</p>",
        "id": 526165712,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071537
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Agda does, so people use this trick a lot over there</p>",
        "id": 526165720,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071551
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and reasonably so, because otherwise you would break Godel?</p>",
        "id": 526165722,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071553
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>no</p>",
        "id": 526165727,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071560
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it's just an incredibly strong assumption</p>",
        "id": 526165735,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071568
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>models of type theory that support I-R types need Mahlo cardinals, not just inaccessibles</p>",
        "id": 526165753,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071588
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, so basically Agda could prove that Type contains a \"universe\", but that universe wouldn't be closed under I-R types?</p>",
        "id": 526165776,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071615
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>right, you could prove the existence of a universe closed under lean style inductives but not I-R</p>",
        "id": 526165803,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>interesting!</p>",
        "id": 526165818,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(although I have to admit I hesitate to assert that because agda allows a lot of stuff)</p>",
        "id": 526165834,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071717
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so basically the entire \"model\" of Lean lives inside Agda's Type 0!</p>",
        "id": 526165838,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1751071735
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>well, actually it's more complicated than that, because Agda has predicative universes</p>",
        "id": 526165856,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071761
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>while Lean has impredicative <code>Prop</code></p>",
        "id": 526165864,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071773
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If agda is consistent, it is probably a subsystem of second order arithmetic</p>",
        "id": 526165900,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071824
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but if you added an impredicative assumption like <code>Prop ~= Bool</code> then Agda would model all of lean comfortably within Type 0</p>",
        "id": 526165944,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751071873
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110049\">Mario Carneiro</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Type.200.20contains.20a.20universe/near/526165720\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Agda does, so people use this trick a lot over there</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>wow I didn't know that</p>",
        "id": 526166253,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1751072326
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm pretty sure \"what kind of inductive types does agda support\" is an open question</p>",
        "id": 526299087,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751236446
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"380294\">Matt Diamond</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/116395-maths/topic/Type.200.20contains.20a.20universe/near/526153499\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>in fact I think the exact value may be independent of Lean</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, it's definitely independent of Lean whether there's a set in Type 0 of inaccessible cardinality.</p>",
        "id": 527184261,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1751636704
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But beyond that, even if every type in Type 0 is smaller than the first inaccessible cardinal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>, I would suspect that it's independent of Lean whether Type 0 itself has cardinality <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>. Type theory is generally  fairly agnostic about a lot of the global structure of universes, so all you really know is that the category of types in Type 0 is equivalent to the category of sets smaller than some inaccessible cardinal.</p>",
        "id": 527184840,
        "sender_full_name": "James E Hanson",
        "timestamp": 1751636891
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes that's definitely the case. the original model in <a href=\"https://github.com/digama0/lean-type-theory/releases/tag/v1.0\">#leantt</a> uses a hierarchy which can be described as \"a strictly monotonic sequence of inaccessible cardinals\", no constraints on using the first omega inaccessibles (but you can use the first omega inaccessibles). That means there are models of lean where Type 0 has no inaccessibles in it, and other models where every universe is a Mahlo cardinal and actually supports I-R (assuming those cardinals exist).</p>",
        "id": 527359406,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1751821342
    }
]